To create a new process, you can use the `fork()` system call. The `fork()` system call creates a new process by duplicating the calling process. The new process is an exact copy of the original, except that it has a unique process ID and a different address space.

Here's an example of how to use `fork()` to create a new process:
```
#include <unistd.h>

int main() {
    pid_t pid = fork();

    if (pid == 0) {
        // This is the child process
        <DO_SOME_WORK_HERE>
    } else {
        // This is the parent process
        <WAIT_FOR_CHILD_HERE>
    }

    return 0;
}
```
In this example, the `fork()` system call is called in the parent process. If it returns a value of 0, then the current process has become the child process and the code inside the `if` block will be executed. If it returns a value greater than 0, then the current process has become the parent process and the code inside the `else` block will be executed.

In the child process, you can do some work and then exit. In the parent process, you can wait for the child process to finish before exiting.

Note that the `fork()` system call is not atomic, which means that it is possible for the child process to call `fork()` itself before the parent process has a chance to do so. This can lead to unexpected behavior, so you should be careful when using `fork()`.

Also note that the child process has its own address space and does not have access to the memory of the parent process. You will need to copy data between the parent and child processes if you need to share data.

